05728nam a22007695i 9780520380462DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021018719  a97805203804627 a10.1515/97805203804622doi  a(DE-B1597)585085  a(OCoLC)1255522950  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aGB665 4aGB665 7aTEC0100302bisacsh04a333.9122300aHydrohumanities :bWater Discourse and Environmental Futures. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (263 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aA free open access ebook is available upon publication. Learn more at www.luminosoa.org. Discourse about water and power in the modern era have largely focused on human power over water: who gets to own and control a limited resource that has incredible economic potential. As a result, discussion of water, even in the humanities, has traditionally focused on fresh water for human use. Today, climate extremes from drought to flooding are forcing humanities scholars to reimagine water discourse. This volume exemplifies how interdisciplinary cultural approaches can transform water conversations. The manuscript is organized into three emergent themes in water studies: agency of water, fluid identities, and cultural currencies. The first section deals with the properties of water and the ways in which water challenges human plans for control. The second section explores how water (or lack of it) shapes human collective and individual identities. The third engages notions of value and circulation to think about how water has been managed and employed for local, national, and international gains. Contributions come from preeminent as well as emerging voices across humanities fields including history, art history, philosophy, and science and technology studies. Part of a bigger goal for shaping the environmental humanities, the book broadens the concept of water to include not just water in oceans and rivers but also in pipes, ice floes, marshes, bottles, dams, and more. Each piece shows how humanities scholarship has world-changing potential to achieve more just water futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aHydrologyxEnvironmental aspects. 0aWater-supplyxEnvironmental aspects. 0aWater-supplyxManagement. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Environmental / Water Supply.2bisacsh1 aDe Wolff, Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFajardo, Kale Bantigue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaletti, Rina C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardy, Penelope K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKane, Stephanie C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlaver, Irene J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez Chavolla, Hugo Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez-Calvo, Ignacio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMostern, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuhammad, Abubakr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMukerji, Chandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrang, Veronica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWescoat Jr., James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators